                {
                    "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/13355783/comment/17278338",
                    "id": "17278338",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jorisvandenbossche",
                        "name": "jorisvandenbossche",
                        "key": "jorisvandenbossche",
                        "avatarUrls": {
                            "48x48": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452",
                            "24x24": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452",
                            "16x16": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452",
                            "32x32": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"
                        },
                        "displayName": "Joris Van den Bossche",
                        "active": true,
                        "timeZone": "Europe/Brussels"
                    },
                    "body": "bq.  We're trying to keep our version spec as wide as possible, and testing against pyarrow 1.x, 2.x, (and soon 3.x) so our users and downstream libraries don't need to upgrade in lockstep with us. I think we'll just have to keep a numpy <1.20.0 bound until we can drop 1.x, 2.x support.\r\n\r\nGenerally speaking (not knowing beam specifically here), I think it should still be possible to support this wide range, and for testing you can pin numpy < 1.20 for the builds testing pyarrow 1.x and 2.x, and not pin numpy on the build testing pyarrow 3.x (without needing to require numpy < 1.20 generally)? \r\n(at least that's what we do for pandas) ",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jorisvandenbossche",
                        "name": "jorisvandenbossche",
                        "key": "jorisvandenbossche",
